<article>
    <h1>In&#xAD;dian-in&#xAD;spired cock&#xAD;tails and con&#xAD;tem&#xAD;po&#xAD;rary In&#xAD;dian street food</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201025/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-25"><time>2020-10-25</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>MASALAA BAR</p>
    <p>Where: 723 East Coast Road</p>
    <p>A fa­mil­iar name is back in the res­tau­rant scene. Vet­eran In­dian chef Milind So­vani, 57, is set to open his 70-seat ca­sual res­tau­rant Masalaa Bar next Sun­day.</p>
    <p>The chef used to helm the kitchens at In­dian restau­rants</p>
    <p>Rang Ma­hal and The Song of In­dia.</p>
    <p>His menu at Masalaa Bar is a con­tem­po­rary take on In­dian street food and In­dian-in­spired cock­tails.</p>
    <p>High­lights in­clude egg ke­jri­wal (sunny-side-up eggs on buns with chilli onion salsa, $8), khau galli kheema pao (minced lamb with buns, $21), pao bhaji (veg­etable melt with gar­lic pao served in a mar­tini glass, $9) and dhaba chicken naan­zaa (pizza-style naan, $15).</p>
    <p>Chef Milind says the prices are his an­swer to those who com­plained about hav­ing to fork out more than $100 for his fine-din­ing cui­sine at his old restau­rants.</p>
    <p>He says he had planned to open a fine-din­ing con­cept ear­lier this year, but put it on hold due to the pan­demic.</p>
    <p>With the un­cer­tainty, he de­cided not to go ahead as In­dian fine din­ing is a “very niche mar­ket” here.</p>
    <p>With other projects in the pipe­line, he be­lieves the fu­ture of din­ing is in cloud kitchens and home de­liv­er­ies.</p>
    <p>“Restau­rants will sur­vive, but peo­ple want con­ve­nience and value-for-money food that can feed a fam­ily,” he says.</p>

